<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-finance-credit-cards" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Credit Cards</title>
  <image source="images/credit-card-image.png" width="50%">
    <shortdescription>A credit card.</shortdescription>
  </image>
<introduction>
  <p>Credit cards are a common source of debt. The Federal Reserve Bank reported that in the second quarter of 2024, Americans 
    owed $1.14 trillion in credit card debt, which is an average of about $4,400 per adult. In this section, we will investigate 
    how credit cards work with the goal of empowering readers to make educated financial decisions.</p>
  </introduction>
    <objectives>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Students will be able to:
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            Identify rates and fees in the "fine print" of credit card agreements.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Calculate average daily balance.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Calculate credit card finance charges using the average daily balance method and the daily balance method.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
           Analyze credit card terms to identify the best options for different types of consumers.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </objectives>
   

    <subsection xml:id="subsec-finance-credit-cards-whatis" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
      <title>What is a Credit Card?</title>
      <p>
        A credit cards is a form of revolving debt. With most loans, such as mortgages or car loans, the money is borrowed all at 
        once and paid back with interest over time. With credit cards, borrowers use the card to make purchases, and they pay back 
        some or all of the amount borrowed each month, and this cycle of borrowing and making payments continues until the account 
        is closed. 
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="How_Credit_Cards_Work">
        <caption>Diagram of three monthly billing cycles of a credit card.</caption>
      <image source="images/How_Credit_Cards_Work.png">
        <shortdescription>Three monthly payments are diagrammed, showing the monthly billing statement generated at the end of each monthly cycle and due 21-25 days into the subsequent cycle. Each bill includes the total spending from the current month, any remaining unpaid balance from the previous month, and a finance charge on the previous month.</shortdescription>
         </image>
    </figure>
      <p>
        Credit card accounts are unique in that if the borrower pays the entire statement balance each month, there is no interest 
        charged on purchases made using the card.  Further, many cards offer rewards to the consumer in the form of cash back, 
        points or miles in rewards programs, or even reducing the balance of a home loan! On the other hand, the if the borrower is 
        unable to pay the entire statement balance each month, they begin to accrue finance charges, which are calculated using the 
        simple interest formula. The interest rates on credit card accounts tend to be significantly higher than those for other 
        types of loans, so borrowers can find themselves amassing a large amount of debt quite quickly. 
      </p>
    </subsection> 
  <subsection xml:id="subsec-finance-creditcard-balance"  xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Credit Card Balances and Finance Charges</title>
    <p>
      The balance in an account typically means the amount of money currently held in that account, whether it is a debt or an investment. With credit cards, the amount owed changes frequently and fees are accrued over time but applied once. As such, there are several different types of balance:
    </p>
  <assemblage xml:id="assemblage-balance-types">
    <title>Types of Balances</title>
    <p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            <term>Previous Balance:</term> the amount of debt carried over from the previous month.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <term>Ending Balance:</term> the amount owed at the end of a billing cycle before finance charges or other fees have been applied.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <term>Statement Balance or New Balance:</term> the total amount shown on the billing statement. It is the sum of the ending balance and any finance charges or fees that are applied at the end of the billing cycle.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <term>Daily Balance or Current Balance:</term> the total balance at a given time. The current balance incorporates any unpaid debt carried over from the previous billing cycle and any activity (purchases, payments, etc.) that have been posted to the account.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <term>Payoff Balance:</term> the total amount a consumer would have to pay to close out the account. It is the sum of the current balance and any prorated finance charges that have accumulated but not yet been applied. (A prorated finance charge is also called residual interest.)
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <term>Average Daily Balance:</term> the average of the current balances on each day of a billing cycle.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p> 
  </assemblage>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A credit card account has the following transactions during the billing cycle: a $500 purchase on January 5, a $200 payment on January 10, and a $100 purchase on January 15. The billing cycle runs from January 1 to January 31. Assume that the previous balance was $1,000 and that a finance charge of $25 is applied at the end of the billing cycle.
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              What is the ending balance for the billing cycle before finance charges are applied?
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              What is the statement balance for the billing cycle?
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              To find the ending balance, we start with the previous balance and add any purchases and subtract any payments. The transactions are as follows:
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Previous Balance: $1,000
                </li>
                <li>
                  January 5 Purchase: +$500
                </li>
                <li>
                  January 10 Payment: -$200
                </li>
                <li>
                  January 15 Purchase: +$100
                </li>
              </ul>
              Therefore, the ending balance is calculated as follows:
              <me>Ending Balance = Previous Balance + Purchases - Payments</me>
              <me>Ending Balance = 1000 + 500 - 200 + 100 = $1,400</me>
              Thus, the ending balance for the billing cycle is $1,400.
            </p>  
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              To find the statement balance, we add the finance charge to the ending balance. The statement balance is calculated as follows:
              <me>\text{Statement Balance} = \text{Ending Balance} + \text{Finance Charge}</me>
              <me>\text{Statement Balance} = 1400 + 25 = $1,425</me>
              Thus, the statement balance for the billing cycle is $1,425.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
        <p>
          To find the ending balance, we start with the previous balance and add any purchases and subtract any payments. The transactions are as follows:
          <ul>
            <li>
              Previous Balance: $1,000
            </li>
            <li>
              January 5 Purchase: +$500
            </li>
            <li>
              January 10 Payment: -$200
            </li>
            <li>
              January 15 Purchase: +$100
            </li>
          </ul>
          Therefore, the ending balance is calculated as follows:
          <me>\text{Ending Balance} = \text{Previous Balance} + \text{Purchases} - \text{Payments}</me>
          <me>\text{Ending Balance} = 1000 + 500 - 200 + 100 = $1,400</me>
          Thus, the ending balance for the billing cycle is $1,400.
        </p>
        <p>
          To find the statement balance, we add the finance charge to the ending balance. The statement balance is calculated as follows:
          <me>\text{Statement Balance} = \text{Ending Balance} + \text{Finance Charge}</me>
          <me>\text{Statement Balance} = 1400 + 25 = $1,425</me>
          Thus, the statement balance for the billing cycle is $1,425.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
    <p>
      When calculating the average daily balance, we find the current balance for each day of the billing cycle and then find the average of those balances. Be careful: this is a weighted average, not a simple average. The balance on each day is weighted by the number of days that balance was held. For example, if the balance was $1,000 for 10 days and $2,000 for 20 days, the average daily balance would be calculated as follows:
    </p>
    <p>
      <me>
        \frac{1000\cdot10+2000\cdot20}{30}\approx 1666.67
      </me>
      Therefore, the average daily balance is approximately $1,666.67.  
    </p>
   <p>
    It can be helpful to write the balances in a calendar or grid to keep track of the balance on each day of the billing cycle. A spreadsheet can also be used to calculate the average daily balance.
   </p>
   <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
      Consider the following transactions on a credit card account during a billing cycle that runs from January 1 to January 31. The previous balance is $1,000.
      <ul>
        <li>
          January 5: $500 purchase
        </li>
        <li>
          January 10: $200 payment
        </li>
        <li>
          January 15: $100 purchase
        </li>
      </ul>
      Find the average daily balance for the billing cycle.
    </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        We will write the balance for each day of the billing cycle in a calendar.
      </p>
      <image source="images/credit-card-daily-bal-calendar1.png">
        <shortdescription>Jan 1-4: $1000, Jan 5-9: $1500, Jan 10-14: $1300, Jan 15-31: $1400</shortdescription>
      </image>
      <p>
        Now we can find the average of the balances in each day of the cycle. We will use multiplication for the repeated addition, and we note that there are 31 days in the billing cycle.
        <me>
          \frac{1000\cdot4+1500\cdot5+1300\cdot5+1400\cdot17}{31}\approx 1348.39
        </me>
        Therefore, the average daily balance is approximately $1,348.39.
        </p>
    </solution>
   </example>
  
    <p>
      A <em>finance charge</em> is the interest charged on the amount owed. It is calculated as the simple interest on the balance on the account. However, there are several ways this can be done. Each credit card agreement will indicate which method is used. Some of the more common approaches are as follows:
     </p>
     <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          <term>Ending Balance Method:</term> The finance charge is calculated using the ending balance. The amount of interest is calculated at the end of the billing cycle and added to the statement balance.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <term>Average Daily Balance Method:</term> The finance charge is calculated using the average daily balance. The amount of interest for each day is calculated and then added together at the end of the cycle.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <term>Daily Balance Method:</term> The finance charge is calculated using the current balance on each day of the billing cycle. The amount of interest is calculated and added each day.
        </p>
      </li>
     </ul>
     <example>
      <title>Finance Charge using Ending Balance Method</title>
      
      
     </example>
     <example>
      <title>Finance Charge Calculation using Average Daily Balance</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose the average daily balance on a credit card account is $5,224.27. Calculalate the finance charge for a 30-day month if the annual percentage rate (APR) is 11.5% and the charge is calculated using each method.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Based on the number of days in the billing period.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Based on one month as one twelfth of a year.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The APR is the annual interest rate, <m>r</m>, and the finance charge is the interest, <m>I</m>, on the balance, <m>P</m>, for the given amount of time.
        </p>
        <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              If the finance charge is based on the number of days in the billing period, then the amount of time in years is <m>t=\frac{30}{365}</m>. Therefore, the finance charge is calculated as follows.
            <md>
              <mrow>I \amp=Prt </mrow>
              <mrow>I \amp=(5224.27)(0.115)\left(\frac{30}{365}\right) </mrow>
              <mrow>I \amp \approx \$49.38 </mrow>
            </md>
            The finance charge is rounded to the nearest cent.
            </p>
            <p>
              An alternative approach is to convert the annual percentage rate to a daily rate <m>\frac{0.115}{365}</m>; then multiply the balance by the daily rate times the number of days. This results in the equivalent calculation
            <me>
              I=(5224.27)\left(\frac{0.115}{365}\right)(31)\approx \$49.38.
            </me>
          </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              If the finance charge is based on just one month, each month is considered one twelfth of a year regardless of how many days it contains. Therefore, we will use <m>t=\frac{1}{12}</m>.
            <md>
              <mrow>I \amp=Prt</mrow>
              <mrow>I \amp= (5224.27)(0.115)\left(\frac{1}{12}) </mrow>
              <mrow>I \amp\approx \$50.07 </mrow>
            </md>
            </p>
            <p>
              An alternative approach is to convert the annual percentage rate to a monthly rate <m>\frac{0.115}{12}</m>; then multiply the balance by the monthly rate times the number of months, which is one. This results in the equivalent calculation
            <me>I=(5224.27)\left(\frac{0.115}{12}\right)\approx \$50.07</me>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
      
      </solution>
      
     </example>
  
    <example xml:id="ex-credit-card-adb">
      <title>Average Daily Balance Method With Time Measured in Days</title>
      
      
      <statement>
        <p>
          A credit card billing period runs from January 23 to February 22. The previous balance is $1,234 and the transactions are listed below.
        </p>
        <tabular row-headers="yes" halign="center">
          <row header="yes">
            <cell>Date</cell>
            <cell>Description</cell>
            <cell>Charge/Credit</cell>
            
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>Jan 27</cell>
            <cell>Mathematical Hardware</cell>
            <cell>$314</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>Jan 30</cell>
            <cell>Payment<mdash/>Thank You</cell>
            <cell>$1,000 (cr)</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>Feb 4</cell>
            <cell>Not Great Clothing (Returns)</cell>
            <cell>$192 (cr)</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>Feb 12</cell>
            <cell>Yummy Chocolate</cell>
            <cell>$30</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>Feb 14</cell>
            <cell>Fancy Restaurant</cell>
            <cell>$120</cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>
        <p>
          Suppose this credit card uses the average daily balance method and charges an annual interest rate of 19.6%. We will find the ending balance, the average daily balance, the finance charge, and the total balance after the finance charge is applied. For calculating the finance charge, this account measures time in days.
        </p>
      </statement>
        <solution>
        <p>
          To find the <em>ending balance</em>, starting with the previous balance, we add the charges and subtract the credits.
          <me>
            1234+314-1000-192+30+120=386
          </me>
          Therefore, the ending balance is $386.
        </p>
        <p>
          To find the <em>average daily balance</em>, we first find the balance at the end of each day. Then we find the average of the daily balances. It can be helpful to write the balances in a calendar or grid.
        </p>
        <image source="images/credit-card-daily-bal-calendar2.png">
          <shortdescription>Jan 23-26: $1234, Jan 27-29: $1548, Jan 30-Feb 3: $548, Feb 4-11: $356, Feb 12-13: $386, Feb 14-22: $506</shortdescription>
        </image>
        <p>
          Now we can find the average of the balances in each day of the cycle. We will use multiplication for the repeated addition, and we note that there are 31 days in the billing cycle.
          <me>
            \frac{1234\cdot4+1548\cdot3+548\cdot5+356\cdot7+385\cdot2+506\cdot9 }{31}\approx$649.55
          </me>
        </p>
        <p>
          Alternatively, a spreadsheet can be used.
        </p>
        <p>
          The <em>finance charge</em> is 31 days simple interest on the average daily balance at 19.6%.
          <md>
            <mrow>I \amp= Prt </mrow>
            <mrow> I\amp=649.55(0.196)\left(\frac{31}{365}\right) </mrow>
            <mrow>I \amp\approx 10.81 </mrow>
          </md>
          Therefore, the finance charge will be $10.98.
        </p>
        <p>
          Alternatively, the annual percentage rate (APR) of 19.6% can be converted to a daily rate of <m>\frac{19.6\%}{365}</m> and multiplied by the number of days. The resulting finance charge calculation results in the same value: 
          <md>
            <mrow> I\amp =P\left(\text{Daily Rate}\right)\left(\text{Number of days}\right)</mrow>
            <mrow>I \amp= 649.55\left(\frac{0.196}{365}\right)\left(31\right)</mrow>
            <mrow>I \amp\approx 10.81 </mrow>
          </md>
  
          
        </p>
        <p>
          To find the total amount owed, we add the ending balance and the finance charge to obtain <m>386+10.81=$396.81</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="finance-credit-fine-print"  xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"> 
    <title>Credit Card Agreements: Reading the Fine Print</title>
    <p>
      A credit card agreement describes the policies and rates which apply to the account. It should contain a table summarizing the interest rates and fees. An example is provided below.
    </p>
    
      <figure xml:id="Credit_card_rates_table">
        <caption>Sample excerpt from a credit card account agreement. A <url href="external/Sample-Credit-Card-Fine-Print-Accessible.docx">screenreader accessible version</url> is available.</caption>
      
      <image source="images/Credit_card_rates_table.png"><shortdescription> Use the link in the caption for a screenreader accessible version of the table in a Microsoft Word document.</shortdescription></image>
      
    </figure>
  <p>
    The For consumers who routinely pay the whole statement balance each month, the APR is of little importance.
  </p>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="finance-credit-payoff"  xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Payoff Balance</title>
    <p>
      The payoff balance is the total amount a consumer would have to pay to close out the account. It is the sum of the current balance and any prorated finance charges that have accumulated but not yet been applied. A prorated finance charge is also called residual interest. It is important for consumers to understand that if they pay off their credit card account, they may still owe some money in the form of residual interest, which can be a surprise to many people. This is because the finance charge is typically applied at the end of the billing cycle, so if a consumer pays off their balance before the end of the cycle, they may still owe interest for the time that has passed since their last statement. Consumers can avoid this surprise by asking their credit card company for a payoff balance, which will include any residual interest, before making a payment to close out the account.
    </p>
    <p>
      One common approach to calculate the payoff balance is to use the simple interest formula to find the prorated finance charge and then add it to the current balance each day. This is known as the daily balance method. 
    </p>

  </subsection>

<exercises xml:id="exercises-finance-creditcards">
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        In general, how can credit-card users avoid finance charges?
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Credit card users can avoid finance charges by routinely paying their entire balance by the due date. 
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        What are the two most commonly used methods of calculating balances that will be used for finance charges?
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        The two most common methods are the daily balance method and the average daily balance method.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Read the fine print of a credit card agreement and identify the method used to calculate finance charges, the annual percentage rate, and any fees that may be applied to the account. If you do not have a credit card, you can find sample agreements at the websites of credit card companies or the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        (Solution would include identifying the specific method, APR, and fees from the credit card agreement.)
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Suppose you have a credit card with an average daily balance of $2,500 and an annual percentage rate of 15%. Calculate the finance charge for a 30-day month if the charge is calculated using each method.
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Based on the number of days in the billing period.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Based on one month as one twelfth of a year.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>

  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        A credit card billing period runs from March 1 to March 31. The previous balance is $800 and the transactions are listed below.
        </p>
        <tabular row-headers="yes" halign="center">
          <row header="yes">
            <cell>Date</cell>
            <cell>Description</cell>
            <cell>Charge/Credit</cell>
            
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>Mar 5</cell>
            <cell>Gadget Store</cell>
            <cell>$200</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>Mar 10</cell>
            <cell>Payment<mdash/>Thank You</cell>
            <cell>$300 (cr)</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>Mar 15</cell>
            <cell>Clothing Store</cell>
            <cell>$150</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>Mar 20</cell>
            <cell>Restaurant</cell>
            <cell>$50</cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>
        Suppose this credit card uses the average daily balance method and charges an annual interest rate of 18%. Find the ending balance, the average daily balance, the finance charge, and the total balance after the finance charge is applied. For calculating the finance charge, this account measures time in days.
      </statement>
  </exercise>
</exercises>  
</section>

